# Hidden Observation

If two words are anagrams,

sorting both words gives the same result.

Example

```text
eat

↓

aet
```

```text
tea

↓

aet
```

```text
ate

↓

aet
```

All become

```text
aet
```

This sorted string is called the **canonical representation (signature)**.

---

# Pattern

## HashMap

### Key

Sorted String

Example

```text
eat

↓

aet
```

Key

```text
aet
```

---

### Value

List of original words

Example

```text
aet

↓

[eat, tea, ate]
```

---

# Data Structure

```java
HashMap<String, List<String>>
```

Meaning

```
Sorted String

↓

List of Original Words
```

Example

```
aet

↓

[eat, tea, ate]
```

```
ant

↓

[tan, nat]
```

```
abt

↓

[bat]
```

---

# Algorithm

### Step 1

Create

```java
HashMap<String, List<String>>
```

---

### Step 2

Traverse every string in the array.

---

### Step 3

Convert the current string into a character array.

```java
char[] ch = word.toCharArray();
```

---

### Step 4

Sort the character array.

```java
Arrays.sort(ch);
```

---

### Step 5

Convert it back into a String.

```java
String key = new String(ch);
```

Now

```text
eat

↓

aet
```

---

### Step 6

Check whether the key exists.

If

```java
!map.containsKey(key)
```

Create a new list.

```java
map.put(key,new ArrayList<>());
```

---

### Step 7

Insert the original word.

```java
map.get(key).add(word);
```

---

### Step 8

After processing every word,

return

```java
new ArrayList<>(map.values());
```

